# Ethical Nudge UX

## Philosophy
Guide users toward their goals with minimal friction, full transparency,
and preserved autonomy. Optimize for user success, not short-term conversion.

---

## Choice Architecture
- Present options in an order that reflects user benefit, not business priority
- Default = the option most users would choose if fully informed
- Limit options to avoid choice overload (max 3–4 alternatives per decision)
- Group related options; separate destructive actions visually

```tsx
// ❌ Avoid: business-optimized default
<Select defaultValue="annual_plan" /> // most expensive

// ✅ Prefer: user-benefit default
<Select defaultValue="monthly_plan" /> // lowest commitment
```

---

## One Primary Action Per Screen
- One dominant CTA per view; secondary actions visually de-emphasized
- Use visual weight (size, color, contrast) to reflect action priority
- The "escape" action (cancel, skip, back) must always be visible

```tsx
// ✅
<Button variant="primary">Create project</Button>
<Button variant="ghost">Cancel</Button>

// ❌ Never hide or disable cancel
```

---

## UX Copy — Action-Oriented Labels
Buttons describe the outcome, not the mechanics.

| ❌ Forbidden | ✅ Required |
|---|---|
| Submit | Send my application |
| Continue | Go to payment |
| Yes | Delete permanently |
| No thanks | Keep my subscription |

Never use confirmshaming: "No thanks, I don't want to save money"

---

## Honest Social Proof Only
```tsx
// ✅ Real data
<p>Joined by 4,200 teams this month</p>

// ❌ Fake/vague
<p>Thousands of satisfied customers!</p>
<p>🔥 12 people looking at this right now</p> // if not real-time
```

---

## Forms — Reduce Friction
- Minimum required fields only; justify each optional field
- Inline validation (on blur), not on submit
- Autofill-compatible field names (`name`, `email`, `tel`)
- Never preselect marketing consent

```tsx
// ❌
<input name="user_email" />

// ✅
<input name="email" autoComplete="email" />
```

---

## Feedback & Progress
- Show progress in multi-step flows (step X of Y)
- Confirm successful actions with specific feedback ("Project saved")
- On error: explain what happened + how to fix it
- Never leave empty states without a suggested next action

---

## Defaults Are a UX Decision
Every default is a nudge. Verify each one:
- [ ] Does this default benefit the user?
- [ ] Is it clearly visible?
- [ ] Can it be changed in ≤ 2 clicks?

If any answer is no → change the default.

---

## SLUDGE — Never Add Friction to Exits
Unsubscribe, cancel, delete, opt-out must be as easy as the reverse action.

```tsx
// ❌ Forbidden patterns
- Cancellation buried in Settings > Account > Billing > Advanced
- Required phone call to cancel
- "Are you sure? You'll lose everything" guilt modals
- Countdown timers on "keep subscription" prompts
```

---

## Timing of Nudges
- Nudge at the moment of decision, not before or after
- Onboarding: guide to first meaningful value in ≤ 3 steps
- Notifications: contextual and actionable only; full user control

---

## Forbidden Patterns (Hard Rules)
NEVER generate code or copy that includes:
- Fake urgency: "Only 2 left!" (if not real inventory)
- Fake activity: "Sarah from Austin just bought this"
- Hidden costs revealed at final step
- Pre-checked marketing consent
- Confirmshaming copy
- Misleading unsubscribe flows
- Modal patterns that obscure the "No" option

---

## Pre-implementation Checklist
Before any nudge, verify:
- [ ] Transparent? User knows what's happening
- [ ] Reversible? User can undo within the session
- [ ] Beneficial? It helps the user's stated goal
- [ ] Ethical? Would you defend it publicly?

All 4 must be true. Otherwise → don't implement.
